The logic you are showing is basically, if A then B, with A being event that can cause a wipe out and B being removal of that event.<br>
<br>
By that same rational you would, logically, have to exclude pulling in any zone or raid where a puller might accidentally overpull.  If puller can overpull then no pulling.<br>
<br>
By that same rational you would, logically, have to exclude any healer in an encounter where mob placement is critical (e.g. VS) because over healing might taunt mob off MA and into the camp resulting in wipeout.  If healing can bring lethal mob into camp, then no healing.<br>
<br>
By that same rational, logically, if there is any chance of an encounter revolving around MA holding aggro, and there is &quot;the slightest possiblity&quot; that the MA might lose aggro and result in a total wipeout, you should not do that encounter.  If the encounter by its vary nature can bring cause a total raid wipeout, then no encounter.<br>
<br>
Yes, the above is absurd.  How can you raid without healing, without pullers, and avoiding any mob that is even slightly threatening?  You can't.  All the above is considered in raiding but instead of having blanket refusal, it is judged as &quot;acceptable risk.&quot;  Healers are judged not only by their ability to heal, but their ability to control their aggro.  Pullers are judged not only by their ablity to get mobs to camp, but also their ability to NOT bring mobs to camp.  Encounters are determined not on the chance that something <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> might</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> go wrong, but if the chance of success warrants the risks it entitles.<br>
<br>
In this case the logic is if A and B then C, where A being event that can cause a wipe out, B being the probability of A happening unacceptably high, and C being removal of that event.<br>
<br>
Now the logic works out to be If the puller might pull too many mobs (A) but we trust the puller not to do it (not B), then they can pull (not C).<br>
<br>
The pet favoring classes are not saying evey situation is correct for a pet.  Obviously it is not.  What we are saying is do not respond to pets in a knee jerk fashion.  Just consider the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> person</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> running the pet and treat them as you would any other class.  If the FD monk puller screws up twice resulting in a raid wipe out, you would boot him.  If the magician's pet causes the raid wipe out, boot him.  But the result of if magician's pet causes raid wipe out, ban pets forever more in that zone, is not logical.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> My raid, my rules. Don't like it? Start organising your own raids.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Agree 100%.  I'll argue till I'm blue in the face here, but know that if I'm ever on a raid with you, and you say no pets, my only response would be yes sir (and maybe a few grumbles with another pet class on the raid, but only to vent).  At leisure is one thing, but in the field there is only the raid leaders words and nothing else matters.<br>
<br>
But as we are at leisure, I once again ask raid leaders and members to please see anti-pet prejudice for what is, a prejudice not based in rational thought.<br>
