Damn straight!  I'm the tankin' mage, with my wardstaff that I can do upwards of <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> 50 points of damage</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->.  My resolution for 2002 was to be SA in a raid.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :lol --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/laugh.gif ALT=":lol"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ulaoke.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Laoke</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 1124<br> <font color=#E9D756>(3/21/02 2:11:46 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrdragonsandplanes.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3183.topic&index=28>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Pets on raids</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> By that same rational you would, logically, have to exclude pulling in any zone or raid where a puller might accidentally overpull. If puller can overpull then no pulling.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
  However, pulling is necessary to advance the raid.  When considering the risk vs. reward, one comes to the conclusion that overpulling is a risk that must be taken.<br>
<br>
  Creating pets in a dangerous area is not.  It's all about risk <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> reduction</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->.  You can never eliminate ALL the risks, but you can minimise the ones that you can control.  Hence, no pets in the Champagne Room.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> By that same rational you would, logically, have to exclude any healer in an encounter where mob placement is critical (e.g. VS) because over healing might taunt mob off MA and into the camp resulting in wipeout. If healing can bring lethal mob into camp, then no healing.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
  You need heals for VS?  Ok, that was facetious (if true : ), but yet again we return to the risk vs. reward idea.  Is the risk of wiping out due to a cleric over healing worse than the risk of wiping out due to no healing?  If it is, then yes I'd be asking all the clerics on the raid to nuke their little hearts out.<br>
<br>
  Pets, as they are an optional extra that is not necessary for a raid to sucede and have the potential in certain areas to wipe an entire raid, are something that you can eliminate as an additional risk simply <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> by not having them up in the first place</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> By that same rational, logically, if there is any chance of an encounter revolving around MA holding aggro, and there is &quot;the slightest possiblity&quot; that the MA might lose aggro and result in a total wipeout, you should not do that encounter. If the encounter by its vary nature can bring cause a total raid wipeout, then no encounter.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
  Since when did loosing a MA = raid wipeout automatically?  Organisation and planning can mitigate the effect of such a result.  However, if you are planning a raid, and you feel that if the MA dies, the raid dies, you should be reasonably sure that you can keep that MA up, or you should change your tactics.  Maybe to one involving pets : )  <br>
<br>
The point I'm trying to make throughout this post is a simple one:  pets are a totally avoidable risk.  You can eliminate them very simply without effecting the raid overly as a whole.  Hence, they are one of the things (along with chaining all paladins to the floor to prevent them roaming to 'mark' their terrority) that a good raid leader has in the back of their mind as a good way to reduce the total risk involved in an encounter.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> But the result of if magician's pet causes raid wipe out, ban pets forever more in that zone, is not logical.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->  <br>
I both agree with this, and don't.<br>
<br>
  Yes, in an ideal world I'd know everyone I raided with and their capabilities.  However, I believe we are talking 'pickup' here.  As in 'Random assemblage of people you wouldn't know from Adam'.  Trying to make a personal judgement in this environment could lead to resentment (Why does he have a pet and I'm not allowed it?), confusion (There's a pet up, I'll cast mine as well!) and ultimately a breakdown in organistion and the chain of command.<br>
<br>
  I've said it many, many times, but the key ingrediant of a successful raid isn't uberness, isn't equipment, isn't levels.  It's <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> organisation</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->.<br>
