<br>
/em hears the cheers across Norrath! <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
However, in response to Antra Immortalis’:<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> if you inspect the mage on a raid and they are not weaing their earthen booties, tell them no pets. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
How about if they are a dark elf who can hide and kill a pet? Or what if they want to have their GEBs or other int boosting boots on to get that benefit and have their earthen hotkeyed in a primary inventory slot?<br>
<br>
And of course, the comment made by my thoughtful opponent in the debate, Laoke:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Pets, as they are an optional extra that is not necessary for a raid to sucede and have the potential in certain areas to wipe an entire raid, are something that you can eliminate as an additional risk simply <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> by not having them up in the first</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> place.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Which is of course the argument I was making from the other side.  In the end, EQ is about risk management.  Level 5s don’t go into Cazic Thule.  A person who is known to wipeout raids doesn’t get invited into them.  Raids don’t go forward if they do not have the type of people they need to succeed.  These are unacceptable levels of risk.<br>
<br>
And thus we get to our impasse, Laoke.  I maintain (steadfastly and without budging because this is my prejudice, if you will), that pets can add to the benefit of a raid by extra damage, off tanks (yes, I have used a pet to off tank in a really bad pull and then killed it the second I saw the blue mez light go off) and disposable fighters who don’t take up healer mana.  Yes, they can cause problems but so can any other participant (AI or RL) in a raid.  As they <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> can</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> help, and <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> can</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> be controlled, in the proper hands, they should be allowed.<br>
<br>
Your point of view is just as valid as mine though (like you really need me to tell you that <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  ), pets can be avoided and still have a successful raid.  Of course, this is true of most of the character classes as well, and members of each of those character classes can be just as devastating to a raid as any pet.<br>
<br>
Therefore, I still see the inconsistency of statements such as<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> If I had a pickup raid of people I didn't know from a bar of soap in ToV, you better believe I'll clamp down a 'Pet and die' edict.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Yet you would allow the monk you don’t know, the bard you don’t know, and the wizard you don’t know, each equally capable of destroying a raid as a rogue pet.  This is the double-standard that spurs me on to post on this thread.<br>
<br>
Having said that, the one thing I utterly agree upon is:<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  Mine is a benevolent dictatorship, but make no mistake: my raid, my rules.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
I think you would be a very interesting raid leader and it is a pity you don’t do pick ups anymore.  But such is life.  However, if by some chance we did end up together on a raid you lead, the second you said no pets, you would never see a Jabaner from me and if I led a group with a pet class that wouldn’t kill theirs, you’d be hearing about it from me.<br>
<br>
But over all, my stance remains the same – pets don’t kill raids, bad pet class players kill raids.<br>
