<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> each equally capable of destroying a raid as a rogue pet. This is the double-standard that spurs me on to post on this thread.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
  I don't think I've explained my viewpoint properly.  My bad.  Here's the deal.<br>
<br>
  <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> My raid, my rules</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->.  It's not just a catch phrase, it implies that I, personally, am responsible for the smooth running of the raid.  I am the first person there, and the last to leave.  I am the one &amp; only authority that matters:  I may delegate authority as I see fit, but when it comes down to it I am the one who's going to get it in the neck if the raid wipes out.  I accept this.  However, this also gives me the divine right (and a pretty good left hook as well) to dictate -exactly- what risks are acceptable, and which are not.<br>
<br>
  In a high-danger area, that means no AE effects at all.  A stated main assist that EVERYONE will use.  2-3 off tankers agreed ahead of time, that everyone knows about.  Pullers are designated and ONLY they go wandering.  No pets.  Clerics who know who they're supposed to be healing when.  Other healers who know their role, be it as a secondary healer or damage dealer.  Necro's who are waiting to pump to save the raid in a crisis.  Enchanters and shamans who are keeping the buffs up.  And absolutely everyone knows the deal with loot before we even <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> start</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> the raid.<br>
<br>
  Yes, it's probably a little restrictive.  I have no problems in areas where things are less critical loosening up:  hell, you should see MF go through PoH one of these days (AE clearance is so much fun : ).  But the point is this:  organisation is <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> key</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->, and responsibility is key to organisation.  And as a responsible raid leader I will make the call as to whether pets are allowed.<br>
<br>
  Often, the answer will be &quot;Hell yes!&quot;.  Remember, most of the mages in MF have their epic, which we affectionately refer to as the tractor.  They're more than capable of off-tanking in low risk areas.  But, in areas where Fluffy would last only slightly longer than a sentance composed by Chiteng that makes sense, it is a huge risk to have them up at all for little reward, compared to the damage output of the raid as a whole.  If the pet is a significant part of the damage output, then I would likely have to question what they hell I was doing in a high threat environment with such a raid composition.<br>
<br>
  So. I'm not hitting out <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> just</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> at pets:  I tend to be very anal about minimising risk for a raid as a whole.  This is because I've seen to many raids wiped out for reasons that could have been prevented by someone taking charge and saying &quot;No, thats a bad idea in this area&quot;.<br>
<br>
